scles, while dermomyotome forms ribs","Dermomyotome forms cardiac muscle, while sclerotome forms skull","Sclerotome forms dermis, while dermomyotome forms vertebrae"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESomites differentiate into two main regions with specific derivatives:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edermomyotome\u003C/strong\u003E develops into skeletal muscles of the trunk and limbs, plus the dermis of the back\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esclerotome\u003C/strong\u003E forms the axial skeleton including vertebrae and ribs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermomyotome forms smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - Smooth muscle actually develops from splanchnic mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerotome forms skeletal muscles\u003C/strong\u003E - Skeletal muscles derive from dermomyotome, not sclerotome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermomyotome forms cardiac muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - Cardiac muscle develops from splanchnic mesoderm in the cardiogenic region\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerotome forms dermis\u003C/strong\u003E - Dermis of the back comes from dermomyotome, while the rest develops from somatopleuric mesoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Somites differentiate into dermomyotome and sclerotome during embryological development.","Sclerotome forms the vertebrae and ribs.","Dermomyotome forms the dermis of the back and skeletal muscles of the trunk and limbs."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56977"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15820"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56977"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:11:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:12:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8511"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71468"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.